  "text": "A retrospective multicenter study reported that culture or pathology of CSF, brain, meninges or spinal cord were positive in 37.7% (26 of 69) of patients. 71.4% of the patients were immunocompromised. [CITATION_1] Antigen was detected in the CSF in 66.0% (35 of 53), antibody by ID or CF in 59.4% (19 of 32) and antigen or antibody in 75% (43 of 57). Detection of antigen in the serum or urine was the basis for diagnosis in 20.1% (16 of 77) in patients with negative findings in the CSF or other CNS tissue. CSF volumes of 10 to 20 mL must be cultured to achieve the highest sensitivity. [CITATION_2] Patients with meningitis may have negative culture, pathology, antigen and antibody in CSF findings but positive results from other sites. [CITATION_3] Repeat antigen and antibody testing and culture or central nervous system (CNS) tissue culture and histopathology may be needed to establish a diagnosis in some patients.",
